 is about a subject that affects most families at some time and I'm very happy that the poem's used by the Institute in whatever way they want,&quot; he said.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;I've only been doing this job - if you can call it that - for a couple of months now but this feels like the work I should be doing as a public poet.&quot;","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"'Exquisite precision'","markupType":"plain_text","type":"crosshead"},{"text":"Professor Paul Workman, chief executive of The Institute of Cancer Research, London, believes the tiny piece of poetry is symbolic of the work being done under the microscope by some of the country's top scientists.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;Simon Armitage's poem engraved on a pill perfectly conveys the exquisite precision of the work the ICR's scientists will be conducting in our new Centre for Cancer Drug Discovery,&quot;","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;The aim is to create a new generation of cancer medicines,&quot; he added.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Speaking over the phone from the new research centre, Armitage concluded &quot;it seems inevitable&quot; this kind of research would soon put an end to cancer as we know it.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;In my lifetime, it's one of those things that people talk about - 'Will we ever see a cure for cancer?'","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;And now, talking to somebody earlier here, they were slightly reframing the question in terms of - 'Can we can we find a way of managing cancer and living with cancer? In a way that's happened with other ailments and illnesses', and so on.","markupType":"plain_text","type":"paragraph"},{"text":"&quot;So it might be that there's a philosophical aspect to this, as well as a medical one.&quot;","markupType":"plain_text","type":"p